column9: TEXT
Ladies and gentlemen, thank you for standing by.
Welcome to Garanti Bank's first quarter 2015 financials, our forecast and conference call.
Our representatives will be Mr. Murat Mergin, Executive Vice President Strategic and Financial Planning and Miss.
Handan Saygin, Senior Vice President, Investor Relations.
(Operator Instructions).
The presentation will now start.
The floor is yours, Mr. Mergin.
Good evening everybody, welcome to Garanti Bank first quarter 2015 financials earnings presentation.
Now I want to kick off as usual with a couple of comments on the macro picture.
First three months of this year have been relatively volatile.
If we look at the global outlook we had ups and downs regarding FED's expected monetary policy decisions.
In January FED's monetary policy normalization was not expected to start in first half of the year.
Second month that reversed, third month it reversed again, so a lot of volatility.
You see that reflected on all indicators.
When we turn to the domestic picture, we've seen the Central Bank hold steady in the last two months of the quarter.

But initially in January they took a decision to cut rates, which in a way led to an upward EPS revision for banks, mainly based on expectation of domestic easing, domestic liquidity conditions which in reality did not prevail so far because of the expected general elections which will take place in June.

So it has been a tight environment, but the Bank was ready for this environment, experienced in such environment and again very strong recurring performance despite the volatility, uncertainty and of course continued, albeit at a lower pace, regulatory charges.
If we look at our Q1 performance compared to Q4 of last year, we defended our NIM quite well through proactive asset pricing and a rather actively managed cost to funding.
A positive surprise for everyone is the growth in net fees and commissions, despite regulatory pressure.
You all remember our guidance regarding net fees and commissions.
We expected flats of single digit contraction maybe because again it is an implementation issue, it's the first year banks are implementing the new draft law on fees.
So we were quite cautious.
We will revise this figure?
Most probably post-Q2 we will revise this upwards.

Looking at our specific provisioning, it's down compared to Q4 of last year because of absence of Romania-related provisions which were booked in Q4 of last year and lower NPL inflows through our subsidiary in Netherlands.

So our core banking revenues were rather flat and as you all know, income on CPI linkers was substantially down compared to Q4 of last year, but on the positive front we had excellent -- and I think we guided for this throughout the year -- excellent progress in collections, which were backed by recoveries in some of the bigger ticket commercial files check collections.
And on the trading and FX, rather contrary to Q4 of last year we have a positive figure.
Again the swap costs were offset by trading gains.

Looking at OpEx we were rather flat, although we had a substantial depreciation of the currency, about 12% year-over-year against the US dollar, which does put pressure on the cost base but nevertheless I think we've done a good job here.
And looking at the regulatory items we still have the continued commission reimbursement-related expenditures.
I think it's in line with what the sector is experiencing currently.
I think it's in line with what the sector is experiencing currently.

All in all our consolidated bottom line was realized at TRY953 million, so in three months of the year, the first three months of the year, we expanded our bottom line by -- compared to last quarter by 16%, year-over-year by about 6% and of course more importantly, including the non-recurring items our ROE was realized a bit under 16% at 15.7%, an excellent ROA at 1.7%.
Moving on to page 4, for the last year or so we've been talking about increased contribution to come from our subsidiaries and we have an itemized list in the back appendix pages.
But in summary, if we look at their contribution, we said they will gradually with each passing year increase their piece of the pie.
Back in 2013 their contribution to bottom line was about 12%, in 2014 moved to 13% and first quarter of this year moved to 18%.
Of course this is not sustainable for the year but it will definitely be around 15%, our estimation.
So an increased contribution will continue.

This 18% is mainly due to some trading gains at GBI, but looking at our major subsidiaries, for example, Garanti Pension Company, net income contribution is all the way up to 5%, Garanti Leasing up to 3% and again, Romania is up to 2%.
So we're quite, quite happy with our financial subs.
For the following pages I'll pass the microphone over to my colleague, Handan Saygin and I'll be here to take questions later on.
Well when we look at the assets growth we've booked on a quarterly basis 5%, a yearly basis 15% growth.
The assets reached TRY259.8 billion.
When you look at the mix of assets, the loans share in assets continued to go up.
It actually reached its peak, realized at the end of March 58.4% loans and assets.
So the lending growth book in the first quarter was 8% versus securities were down 4%.
Moving on to the next page, looking at the securities book contrary to the loans the securities hit its lowest level in assets, 15.5%.
We had some redemptions in the quarter on the TL side, mainly from the TL fixed rate portfolio and the CPI linker portfolio.
We had replaced these redemptions with some new additions and new additions were mainly the CPI linkers.
Overall the TL securities book dropped by 7% in the quarter and 9% on an annual basis.
The foreign currency securities, we also had a drop there as well.
We booked some trading gains, the shrinkage in foreign currency book reflects some trading activity.
It was mostly from the FRN portion, so the FRN weight in total securities went down to 59% this quarter, even though it's up on the TL portfolio to 74% from 73% at year end.
The FRN portion in foreign currency dropped 8% from 16%.
So total securities book, when we look at the drop, was 4% in the quarter and the securities book reached TRY42.6 billion.
During the first quarter end the unrealized mark-to-market losses pre-tax was TRY134 million versus the gain that was booked at year end of TRY79 million.
Moving on to page 7, the cautious stance in lending with sustained focus on profitability continued.
So we booked some market share gains in TL and total loans.
In total lending the annual growth corresponded to 17%, the quarterly growth was 8%.
It was predominantly driven by business banking loans.
Total lending reached TRY153.8 billion.
On the TL side the quarterly growth was 7%, 19% on an annual basis.
On the foreign currency side we had some shrinkage in the quarter, it was 3%, annual basis it was 5%.
These are in dollar terms.
And in the quarter the volatility and the uncertainties weighed on the demand.
But moving on to the next page, what basically drove the growth, we continued emphasis on high margin retail products.
In retail lending we've booked a 13% annual growth, in the quarter the growth was 3%.
Mortgage growth was 4% in the quarter, annually it was 14%.
Credit card balance growth was flattish in the quarter, but the annual growth was 3%.
In auto loans the quarterly growth was 3%, annual basis it was 11%.
In general purpose lending it was 4% in the quarter and 18% year-on-year.
I mean in terms of market share we're leader in mortgages, so it's 13.5%, in auto loans 22.9% and consumer lending 13.8%.
We had -- in the quarters we had market share gains in lucrative products like GPLs and auto loans and we continue having our leading position in credit cards business.
In terms of number of credit cards we have 14.2% market share, we're leaders and also in terms of acquiring volume with over 20% market share we have this, we rank second.
Moving on to the asset quality we have guided, we have some anticipated NPL inflows, but those were sorted out with strong collection.
The NPL ratio on a bank-only basis continued to stay way below the sector average at 2.3% versus 2.7% of the sectors.
On a consolidated basis there has been slight improvement.
It came down from 3% to 2.9% end of first quarter.
Looking at the overall NPL -- new NPL inflows, there have been -- those have been lower versus fourth quarter inflows and inflows were mainly from the unsecured lending as guided.
Collections performance was very strong.
The collections were TRY300 million in the quarter and it was across all segments.

Looking at by business line, retail banking NPL, we (inaudible) versus sectors as we had seen in the past couple of quarters some NPL portfolio sales mainly linked to retail and credit card portfolios.
In retail banking NPLs they went up to 2.7% from 2.6%.
In credit cards the NPL ratio, again there's about 10 basis points iteration there, went up to 4.7%.
In business banking side though we see some improvement, 20 bps improvement coming down to 1.8, so the gap has widened, between the sectors has widened a bit.
Looking at the cost of risk in the quarter, the specific cost of risk booked was 100 basis points, but it was half offset with some collections.
So net specific cost of risk ended up in the quarter with 50 basis points and that is way below what we booked in -- actually more than half of what we booked in fourth quarter.
So very happy with the net specific cost of risk performance.
On the general cost of risk it was 53 basis points.
The contribution that was from the regulation-related impact was limited because this quarter we started reversing provisions relating to obtaining export loans.
So that offset a large portion of the regulatory -- because they're a required provision.
So the regulations impact was only 6 basis points and the general cost of risk at 47 basis points.
When compared to fourth quarter last year it's significantly above, I would say, but that has to do with the currency depreciation and also strong collections during the quarter.
So overall when you look at the net cost of risk, the net cost of risk is in line with budget and the general provisioning burden likely will be sorted out in the coming quarters.
Moving on to the funding, the customer-driven and expanding deposit base we continued seeing.
Our concentration in lower ticket, lower costs, sticky type deposits continued.
A good indicator to that is that the consumer and SME in TL deposits went up to 83% from 79% at year end.
But when we look at the total deposit growth, or total TL deposit growth, it was 1% in the quarter.
And on the foreign currency deposits it was slightly lower; we shrank by 1% in the quarter on a consolidated basis.
On a bank-only basis though the foreign currency deposits were up by 2%, versus sector's 4%.
So deposit growth-wise, watching the costs, so we were more prudent, I would say.
On the demand deposits side our success story continues and our demand deposits on a yearly basis went up by 18%.
Our demand deposits share in total deposits continued to stay way above the sector's average, consolidated ratio was 23%, bank-only figure was 21% versus sector's average at 18%.
Loan to deposit ratio deteriorated just slightly due to lower deposit growth but still remained below the 110%, the reported figure was 109%.

When we adjust the loan to deposit ratio with those loans that are funded with only long term other sources of funding that are on balance sheet the ratio drops down to 76.9% and this is another alternative way of looking at the ratio and this is what gives us still comfort regarding the loan to deposit ratio.
On the capital front we maintained the robust capital ratios.
The CAR reported was 13.3%.
There has been about 60 basis points lower.
Mainly it's because of the currency effect, 61 basis points is the currency effect and 8 basis points relates to mark-to-market losses.
The sensitivity of the currency depreciation, for every TRY0.10 increase affects the CAR ratio about 19 basis points.
You know we have the highest tier 1 ratio amongst peers, about 92% of our total capital is tier 1.
In terms of also highest free funds interest earning assets again we rank higher versus peers.
Moving onto the yields and costs page, loan yields and deposit costs.
Loan yields remains resilient.
We have been re-pricing upwards, especially on the consumer side, like in mortgages we re-priced in the quarter about 30bps, GPL by 55 bps, auto loans by 70bps.
Those helped to keep our loan yields at a higher level.
Total loan yields drop in the quarter was about -- was only 7bps in the quarter, blended with the TL and FC.
We refrained from uneconomic pricing both on the lending and the deposit side.
On deposits also the average cost went up in time deposits by only 12 basis points in the quarter on a blended basis.
Mainly the upwards pressure was mainly driven by the competition as well as the deposit pricing that we saw at year-end.
Also of course the lingering volatility and uncertainties in global and domestic markets.
Looking at NIM.
The NIM drop was 49 basis points in the quarter, but that included the effect of the CPI linkers.
As we mentioned earlier, the CPI linker revenues were almost halved.
So excluding the CPI linkers volatility, income volatility, the NIM contraction was limited, so it was only 10 basis points in the quarter.

Positive contribution to NIM mainly came from lending and funds borrowed and bond issuances in the quarter, dimmed by negative income volatility of CPI linkers as well as the higher quarterly average deposit cost.
Looking at net fees and commissions, we maintained a positive growth in fees.
This is upside to the guidance, as we pointed out earlier, despite the new regulatory environment.
In the net fees and commissions on an annual basis the growth is about 2%.
We still have the highest -- and we maintained the highest net fees and commissions market share.
Our market share in this is about 16%.
An emphasis is placed in net fees and commissions on diversified and untapped areas to alleviate regulatory pressures.
Main contributors were payment systems fees.
We had better than expected performance in the first quarter.
Leadership in acquiring business and focus on commercial credit cards definitely helped to deliver a better result.
Non-cash loan fees, again, we had better than expected performance there.
In insurance, again that was another area the performance was better than anticipated.

We are the most preferred pension company, with 17.2% market share in terms of number of participants and we're number one in bancassurance per premium production which basically directly affects the fee generation.
On brokers again, that was another area we had better than expected performance.
In money transfer fees again that was a good contributor.
We have leadership in interbank money transfers with over -- with nearly 16% market share.
Again, the effective utilization of digital channels contributed as well to the net fee and commission generation.
When we move onto the next page, 17, the OpEx figure.
The non-HR related costs weighed on OpEx.
The reported figure in the quarter was, on an annual basis, 22% growth.

But this figure included two items, one is the founder share tax penalty payment that hit the OpEx, which we had provided for it in the provisions line, we had booked reversal, so the effect of the bottom line has -- there has not been an effect to the bottom line related to that.
The other item is the worse than expected commission reimbursement, including related litigation expenses.
In the quarter it was TRY75 million.
When we adjust the OpEx for these two items the 12% operating expense growth comes in line with what we guided in the budget.
The first quarter effect was slightly worse I would say.

Again, there's some currency depreciation effect as currency depreciated by about 12% in the quarter, so there is slight, also, contribution of the depreciation to our OpEx performance in the first quarter.
When we look at our efficiency ratios we're still number one in terms of ordinary banking income per branch, loans per branch and customer deposits per branch versus the peer average.
Our OpEx and average assets were maintained at 2.2%.
Well, our differentiated business model once again yielded strong results when we look a year-on-year basis.
We booked very strong core banking revenues and 19% annual increase in core banking revenues, despite the market volatility and regulatory charges.
We are committed to profitable growth and for higher loan to deposit spread year-on-year, that will be backed with dynamic asset liability management.
We're committed to deliver diversified fee base and also the reshaped business model in that respect continued to pay off.
The annual year-on-year net income growth booked was 6%.
We ended up the first quarter of the year with TRY953 million.
This [represents] our presentation, we can take your questions.
Ladies and gentlemen, the meeting floor is now open for a Q&A session.
(Operator Instructions) We are taking the first question.
Oh hi, good afternoon, thanks for the call.
Perhaps you could just talk a little bit about your loan appetite.

I mean for what you call a period of high volatility you've had some quite decent growth figures in terms of your lending, particularly obviously in business banking but actually pretty decent in the retail side.

Perhaps could you talk a little bit about how you've been approaching what's been not that easy an environment where growth has been under a certain amount of pressure, funding costs have been very tight.
What's your view on the outlook for demand and how have you been dealing with that?
That would be useful to understand where your interests are and whether they're changing at all versus the budget that you gave us at the beginning of the year.

Then I guess secondly on the margin, perhaps you could just talk us through a little bit more in more detail how January, February, March has gone and what you feel we should be looking for over the next couple of months when the disappointment, I guess, has been that funding costs have not really started to come down.
So that would also be helpful to give us an understanding of what the current market conditions are.
It's true that the positive surprise in fee income appears to be something that's generally shared by the industry or at least your peers that have reported so far.
Do you think this is a greater focus to try and compensate margin pressure in other areas?
Why is it starting to pick up now when clearly your view a couple of months ago was things will be much more difficult?
Hi [Alan], I'll start from your last question.

Again, our guidance, when we gave our guidance regarding fee and commission collections, our reasoning was quite simple, we said we have a new draft law in place where there are a lot of implementation issues and we in fact quoted a period probably first half of the year or at least eight months of the year to see how perfect Turkish banking system will implement this draft law.
So based on the first three months of the year the Turkish banking system is doing a better than expected job.
I hope this continues.
Again, in the beginning of the presentation I talked about seeing quarter 2 before we revise our guidance regarding fees and commissions for the whole year.
But I can tell you now it will not be a flat year or a contraction year regarding fees and commissions.
Of course, there's better or relatively tighter attention on fee and commission collection but overall I think the banking system is doing a better than expected job.

Coming back to your first question, again, if you look at page 14, if you look at our upward loan re-pricing in the period it's not bad, 30 basis points in mortgages, 55 basis points in GPL, 70 basis points in auto loans.
It is not a bad performance because that's ultimately going to affect our loan yields positively going forward.
Again, we were able to underwrite these at levels which we thought were quite economic.
Deposit costs we feel were economic.
Deposit costs we feel were elevated because of, again, volatility regarding what's happening domestically and, of course, uncertainties in global conditions.
I mean our feeling is once FED is able to take its decision a lot of the uncertainties will evaporate.
Yes, there will be new pricing levels but any way you look at the picture the average deposit costs today are offering quite good spreads to expected inflation, for sure.
We think these are elevated.
Not the levels they should be at.
Another milestone, which is domestic, is the elections.
Once we're through with the elections we think Turkey will get back on its back to business mode and will get back to business.
We think the Central Bank will be able to take timely and better decisions regarding future monetary policy.
So that was our reasoning for grabbing market share.
Your second question was regarding NIM.

If you look at the NIM page we had a -- if you look at the quarterly evolution of components we had a positive coming from loans, but of course you have to consider the duration mismatch between loans and deposits.
Deposits are short and, of course, as I said they were elevated.
So we had a negative 20bps contribution to margin evolution, but loans, of course, are longer dated.
They're able to be sustained.
Of course, CPI linkers is not a surprise because of our accounting methodology, which is the realized inflation rate, we had a negative 37 basis points impact, which will be different in Q2.
The other items are flat across the base.
I don't know if I've been able to answer your questions but the ex-CPI contraction in NIM, about 10 basis points, was guided.
No, as always that was really helpful.
We are taking the next question.
Good afternoon, thank you.
Thank you very much.
Just a couple of questions on my side.
They're broadly focused on asset quality and OpEx.
So I have four, so I'm just going to -- I'm just going to go through them all.

My first one is how sustainable is your collection performance and where there's quite chunky collections in 1Q that kind of resulted in that very high collection performance and how would you on our side see it developing going forward?
So that's my first.
My second one is really how do you see the NPL performance from here?
I think you've indicated that the new flows were largely consumer, as expected -- as you communicated earlier in the year.
But I'm more interested in what are you seeing on the SME and commercial side and how that flow is evolving.
Of course, if you could give us a couple of words of wisdom on the sensitivity to potential further depreciation of lira versus US dollar, versus the basket and how you see that sensitivity changing?
My third question is about what is the remaining ability of guarantee to reverse the general provisions on SME and export loans and if you have a number for us that would be very useful.
My last one is really on OpEx and your sensitivity to US dollars, how sure shall we think about it going forward?
How sensitive is your OpEx to potential further depreciation?
I will start with your first question the collection performance.
The first quarter collection performance is not a sustainable performance because it does include some one-off recoveries from those.
I mean in the past we recorded those commercial files separately, so we had a chunky collection in the first quarter from commercial files.
I would just stick to our annual guidance in terms of collection performance.
Our annual guidance was that we do expect 40% improvement in total collections in the year.
Now the first quarter was quite sizeable, but then it still suggests the 40% improvement for the whole year still suggests that the ensuing quarters also will not be bad.
Regarding NPL performance, again as we stick to our guidance.
We do expect NPL inflows coming from unsecured lending, mainly general purpose loans and credit cards.
We did start seeing some slowdown but maybe it is too early to change.
Regarding the foreign currency book, we are not expecting any downside surprise there, any negative surprise there.
So again we stick our yearly guidance regarding the NPL performance.
Our guidance for the year was about 20, 30 deterioration in the NPL ratio if you recall.

Regarding your third question, reversal of general provisions--actually we have that on Page 10, it is very small print, on the lower right hand side--the regulatory charges that hit the first quarter was TRY73 million but then the provision reversal amount was TRY51 million in the quarter.
I hope that answers the question.
Going to your last question, the OpEx sensitivity to currency depreciation--I would say about 10% of our OpEx is linked to currency.
So that should give you a good grab on the currency effect on OpEx.

Just very quickly, on the first question, I saw what happened the first quarter but I am just wondering how much more of the general provisions can you actually reverse potentially in the quarters to come?
Or is that TRY51 million it?
TRY51 million you can expect in the end, for each quarter in the next three quarters.
That's brilliant.
The accumulated amount was about TRY200 million, TRY200 million plus, so expect around TRY50 million for each quarter.
Okay that's clear.
The second, the currency sensitivity on your OpEx is it largely Euro or is it dollars?
Well I mean 10% of the OpEx is currency linked.
I mean there are--majority is dollars; majority dollars I would say.
Alright.
Perfect.
If you would like to ask a question, please press pound key then seven one.
We are taking a question that came through web.
The question is by [Tania Mischankena] and the question is you have mentioned that you saw a strong growth in retail segment, how much of that do you expect to translate into NPL this year?
That is one.
The second question is, would you please indicate loan and deposit growth guidance for the full year 2015?
I leave the floor to presenters for the answers.
I will start with the second question.
The guidance for 2015 in terms of lending growth is 15% for Turkish lira loans and 8% for foreign currency loans.
For deposit growth the guidance is 13% in 2015.
This would be 8% from foreign currency loans in dollar terms and 11% in TL.
Deposits; yes, deposits.
I am sorry, deposit growth.
The first question, yes we did see some strong growth in retail segment.
How much of that do you expect to translate into NPL this year?
Well our NPL guidance for year end is that deterioration of about 20 to 30 basis points.
We expect the NPL ratio to reach to 2.7% and that ratio includes also the expected NPL inflows that are related to the loan originations this year.
Thank you very much.
We are taking another question (inaudible).
Apologies.
I should have asked all my questions in one go.
But I am just curious whether your outlook for interest rates and inflation has changed over the last three months?

You kind of know what your budget was based on, but given how the funding markets have behaved, given what is happening with the potential (inaudible) and those expectations kind of changing, how do you see the interest rates, kind of the monetary policy effectively developing from here?
I would be kind of interested to hear not only about the repo rate but also about your view of the corridor and also inflation, that particularly taking a couple of last trends into account.
Actually we have not changed our interest rate assumptions lately.
I mean there is no official guidance yet, official changes in macro assumptions.
On the inflation front, you know the currency past through, like we make calls as expected by the market slump, downside risk for inflation meaning higher inflation.
Our inflation expectation is moving more towards 7% range rather than what we--in the budget it was a lower figure we had.
It was 5.9% for October to October and 6.1% for year end.
So maybe another percentage increase in inflation it seems likely.
In that case that would be an upside risk for the CPI revenues for us.
But I mean at this point in time we have not officially changed the rates of the inflation guidance.
Okay, let me maybe put it the other way.

We have seen the pretty much, the vast majority of your funding curves remaining stubbornly high in Turkish lira and so do you expect with the Fed actually hiking, let's just say in December this year, by how much do you think that those rates are likely to go up into the beginning of 2015?
Versus the beginning--
(Inaudible) and Turkish lira rates.
Turkish lira rates, we think they are going to stay put until the year end.
Thank you very much.
These rates will--I mean at this point this is what we anticipate.
We are taking the next question.
I wanted to touch a little bit on your current thoughts on the guidance given the trends we have seen in the first quarter -- maybe if I could just recap.

I do not want to put words in your mouth, but hopefully you will confirm or infirm what I am saying here, but it sounds like on lending you are doing okay, still likely to hit what you were expecting.
On margins, again you sounded like so far so good.
A little bit better on fees.
But then what is going on on costs?
We have seen quite a significant increase year-on-year and I guess your target of 11% to 13% would have included some of these one-off, the TRY81 million probably not fully the rebate.

Do you think there is a very good chance that that cost guidance will need to be increased or do you think there are some things you could do to cut costs or bring the cost growth sort of under control later in the year?
Cost guidance, these penalties or the tax payments were not included, because when we give a guidance on OpEx it is purely operating expenditures.
If you look at the nature of these payments they are not really OpEx.
They are tax payments or tax penalties or fines.
So that is why we show excluding those one-offs, because I am not expected to be fined again regarding the Founder Share transaction which occurred eight years ago or so.
So including those, excluding those we are on track, approximately right on the dot on track.
Sorry, but you had provided for the TRY81 million right, so that was sort of, you were expecting--
But that is not on operating expenditure.
But not on the OpEx.
So in your original guidance on OpEx that was not included and for the fee rebate how much were you factoring in for that and what does the run rate suggest, some sizeable upside risk there?
The fee rebate side, I will speak very cautious, because looking at the sector data it is going above anybody's expectations.
But again there will be some actions we at Turkish banks will take in the upcoming months regarding the fee reimbursements, but currently it is above expectations.
Honestly, I will be very cautious in saying you know take this as a run rate for the next three quarters.
I would not take it because again there are some items which Turkish banks will take action on and hopefully that will eliminate some of the pace that is occurring today in Turkey.
Okay and apart from these better revenues and maybe some cost pressures you feel pretty comfortable on the rest of the guidance or would you flag or anything else?
No, I mean on the guidance, the biggest positive as I said is fees and commissions.
Again it is quite quite early for us--and again being very cautious--to revise any of the figures.
But today I can safely say there will be a positive revision for fees and commissions.
By what number we will probably tell you when we do the Q2 earnings announcement.
Other than that I would not change anything today.
That is great.
Hi again.

I just thought perhaps you could give us a little bit more colour on the dynamics within the business banking area in terms of is what we are seeing a fair amount of shift or large corporates from their FX lending into TL lending?
Where do you see the dynamics in the SME market?
Any colour you can provide in terms of what is happening within that overall envelope of business banking would be really helpful.
Business banking [Alan] was largely the orphan in the family.

As Turkish banking system we thoroughly covered corporates and big commercial companies and they did not pay a lot of attention to SMEs as Turkish banking system that is why they were very under-penetrated.

IF you look at the last six years in Turkish banking system, brand size has expanded and of course Garanti being an early entrant into this segment we saw (1) margin spreads in this segment are much better and (2) collateralisation in this segment is quite quite better, but underwriting is not so easy as a corporate.
Why?
The financials of SMEs you have to be very adapt at knowing the company, knowing the shareholders, knowing the sector, because most of the time not everything is booked on the financials.
For example, many of the financial assets are with the shareholder of the company and liabilities are with the company.
So if you try to base your underwriting on this picture much of the time your answer will be no.  Therefore brand size is a necessity.
You have to be on ground, you have to know the sector, you have to know the company.
In terms of demand, the demand is quite strong because the regulatory decisions taken about two years ago favor lending to the business segment.
As you know the GLLP or capital charges versus the consumer segment is much more advantageous.
Add on top of that healthy spreads.
Add on top of that good collateralization.
It is a no-brainer and much of the lending in this segment is Turkish lira.
So going forward they are definitely going to be one of the two leading segments if not the leading segment in Turkish banking.

As long as the country continues on the growth trajectory--that is an important parameter--and looking at Turkey, yes we are growing below the historical 5% average, but nevertheless if we look around Europe or our region, we are one of the highest growing countries through thick and thin.
All the volatility regarding Fed, Euro Zone, anything and everything, Turkey is still growing and we still have healthy finances in the country.
So for a bank like Garanti who has invested significantly into this segment, if we are able to capture market share at economic returns, we will take it.
There have been periods in the past as well when a lot of the banks shied away.
We grabbed market share.
When competition gets really heated, we usually step back.
But when there is less competition we do grab market share because we do grab our expected returns.
So when I look at that 10% growth quarter-on-quarter in the TL business banking loans in Q1 is that being driven by SME lending or is it being driven by larger corporates?
It's mainly SMEs and small commercial companies, which again, and I have to stress this, [all/or] for better spreads versus corporates and better collateralization versus corporates.
Super.
That's really helpful.
No problem.
We are taking the (technical difficulty).
Good evening.
I just have two quick questions.
First of all is a follow-up question regarding this strong growth.
Taking your cautious stance in the first quarter regarding the growth, your growth numbers, especially in some segments are quite promising to me.
You're growing in mortgages, in GPLs and at least credit card balances are not shrinking at all.
This growth is accompanied with operative pricing in your marginal files.
So my question is shall we expect this much growth and this much -- or this trend is upward, the pricing trend in the next quarter?
